<h3>Is the quality of work done by offshore IT staff good enough?</h3>
<p>Quality is very good with IT web developers. We find in many cases you can access more specialised and more experienced talented web developers with HTML, asp.net, PhP, MySql and MsSql and some offshore staff could very well be more advanced than some of your local staff. We have found some of our clients with in-house IT staff at $80k are not as advanced as the offshore staff working remotely for $17,000 per year. This happens on a number of occasions.</p>

<h3>Is the quality of work done by offshore Marketing staff good enough?</h3>
<p>We have great success with Search Engine Optimisation (SEO) staff. Although the market is not flooded with SEOs, the people we have access and experience have proven to be able to do quality work. Finding Search Engine Marketing (SEM) staff can be more challenging. This is because the socio-economic restraints in the Philippines restrict people from placing advertisements on Google AdWords. This restricts the quantity of offshore staff available with this type of experience.</p>
<p>We have no problem finding link builders, bloggers, directory and article submissions, online bookmarking and other offshore staff who know how to marketer using social networking skills online.</p>
<p>The market has a good standard of English writers; we have no problem finding article & product writers, press release or website review writers, writers to do transcriptions and online research.</p>


<h3>Will I be able to manage and work with a remote team like I could work with my local staff?</h3>
<p>Typically, we would often hire someone new and leave it up to them to get the job done. As employers, all we care about are the results. Often, this approach doesn’t work as well when starting out with offshore staff because having staff work remotely from you can create disassociation in their first few weeks. They are still learning your business and discovering how your business operates.</p>

<p>Offshore staff are very good at following directions. It is important when working with offshore staff to provide instructions clearly. This will enable your offshore staff to get the job done accurately. We recommend you use verbal, written and remote screen share to show and demonstrate the job and work requirements you want done. It’s important to make your remote staff feel as if they are part of your local team. If possible having them part of meetings using technology will increase their sense of being part of your team. We find commitment, morale and quality of work is higher when this occurs.</p>

<p>Thanks to technology, working with offshore staff is like having them just down the hall in your office. With screen share technology, you can show your offshore staff what you have on your computer screen, making it easy to communicate when showing or explaining tasks. With soft phones, you can have an international phone number to call your offshore staff at a local call cost. With Remote Staff tools such as Google docs, sharing documents and keeping in touch with workflows and TO DO list is easy. Instant messenger services with Skype helps keep communication constant and live. In addition, you will be able to see your Remote Staffs computer screen every 5 minutes, making it easy to see the flow of work as it happens.</p>

<h3>Will I get the flexibility and commitment from the offshore staff?</h3>
<p>Yes. Offshore staff are eager and driven to learn and work with foreign companies because they find it more prestigious and see it as a good career move. Working with international employers also gives them a variety of experiences and a more challenging working and learning experience which is very much valued.</p>

<p>What we have found is if a small bonus of $25 is given, you will sometimes manage to get 15 hour work days from some staff. Try achieving that with local in house staff!</p>

<p><strong>Please note: </strong>no bonuses are to be offered directly to offshore staff, even though they are dedicated to work with you directly, you will need to submit bonus and overtime requests through to the Think Innovations Remote Staff team located in Australia.</p>

<h3>Will the job get done to the standards I need?</h3>
<p>It’s difficult to generalize, but we found that it depends on the person we hire for you. Our success rate at the moment is 85% that the person our recruitment and HR team select for you will be an asset, as long as a bit of training is offered when starting out and clear expectations are set. To protect you from this concern, Remote Staff offers you a candidate replacement as many times as you like over the first month or two, giving you the client, the best odds in finding the right remote staff to get the job done to your expectations.</p>

<h3>Is their English good enough?</h3>
<p>Yes, the staff's English are fluent enough for them to be effective, efficient and functional on whatever position they’ll be hired for. We only hire staff that have fully functional spoken and written English. More often than not, conversing with Filipinos in English is easier than conversing with many people of non-Indigenous English speaking countries. This is due to the fact that Filipinos have formally learnt English at schools as it is the country’s co-official language. School books are written in English and Hollywood movies are never translated nor subtitled in their local language.</p>

<p>If there is a language barrier issue, it may be more to do with accent rather than English speaking abilities. Depending on the job role and your requirements, we will seek out those who can speak with a neutral accent. The Remote Staff have a slight American accent..</p>

<h3>Will they be able to work well independently?</h3>
<p>Yes. Micromanaging is neither needed nor encouraged, and just like any local staff member, assistance on the first 2 weeks will be necessary. You need to give them a week or two to adjust to the nature of your business or industry and give as much product information as you can to help them get started with you. The more the staff understand your business, the more they will be able to have some foresight and be able to see the full depth in the job that might be needed.</p>

<h3>Are they trustworthy individuals we can rely on?</h3>
<p>Trust is on the top list of the values we adhere to. We assess and guide all the staff we hire to share these values. We have legal representation in the Philippines and a fund set aside to enforce our legally binding contractual agreements that all offshore staff agree and sign before commencement of work. Remote Staff values trust and we demonstrate this by legally protecting your proprietary confidentiality and intellectual property.</p>
